  "transcript": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "The quiet of an afternoon feels perfect for a calm chat. How are your NEET PG prep sessions going?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Not great, to be honest. I pulled an all-nighter yesterday and my mind is so foggy. The books just... *bhag*! They won’t stop haunting me even in dreams."
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Right, all-nighters leave that heavy fog in the morning. It’s no joke when books chase you even in dreams — what part feels most overwhelming right now?\""
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "The clinical cases and differential diagnoses — they all just blur together. I read something, then forget it 10 seconds later. My eyes are burning too. Should I take a break or push through?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Those clinical cases are tough — it’s normal for them to blend after a long stretch. Burning eyes and a tired mind don’t help. A short walk or a warm cup of tea might reset things. What’s your go-to fix when it gets too much?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "A short walk sounds nice, but I might just crash on the couch for 20 minutes. Coffee is my usual go-to, but I’m trying to cut back because it messes with my sleep. Maybe a peppermint tea? It wakes me up a bit without the jitters."
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "A 20-minute couch nap is wise — your brain needs the reset. Peppermint tea is a smart swap, gentle and refreshing. Did you try it during past study breaks, or is this a new experiment?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "No, it’s a new thing. I usually stick to green tea, but it wasn’t cutting it yesterday. A friend suggested peppermint — says it helps her focus. I’ll give it another try. But if I don’t get this differential diagnosis stuff soon, I’ll lose my mind."
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "A friend’s recommendation is a good sign — peppermint might just be the spark you need. Let’s face it, differential diagnoses are a beast. What’s the one part you feel almost ready to crack?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Maybe the history-taking part — like, figuring out which symptoms point to which systems. But once the cases get complicated, with multiple overlapping signs, I get stuck. It’s like solving a puzzle blindfolded. *sigh*"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "History-taking is definitely the starting point — it’s like laying the puzzle pieces out first. Once you map the symptoms, the rest becomes clearer. What’s your trick for keeping track of them all?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I try to make quick notes in bullet points — like, which symptom relates to which system — but sometimes I mix them up. Maybe I need to color-code them? Or maybe I’m just overthinking it. What do you think?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Quick bullet points are a good start — they keep things simple. Color-coding could help, but only if it doesn’t add more stress. What if you tried just one case with colors and see how it feels?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Maybe I'll try that. One case with color highlights — red for neurological, blue for cardiological... something like that. Thanks, Maya. I think I need this tiny shift more than I realize. Gotta go now, my next study block is starting. Talk to you later."
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Got it — one colored case at a time. Tiny shifts do the heavy lifting. Go tackle it, and take your time. Talk soon!\""
    }
  ],
